{
    "word": "Gallows",
    "definitions": [
        "A frame from which is suspended the rope with which criminals are executed by hanging, usually consisting of two upright posts and a crossbeam on the top; also, a like frame for suspending anything.",
        "A wretch who deserves the gallows.",
        "The rest for the tympan when raised.",
        "A pair of suspenders or braces."
    ],
    "examples": [
        "So they hanged Haman on the gallows.",
        "If I hang, I'll make a fat pair of gallows.",
        "O, there were desolation of gaolers and gallowses!",
        "At length him nailgallow tree."
    ],
    "etymology": "[OE. galwes, pl., AS. galga, gealga, gallows, cross; akin to D. galg gallows, OS. & OHG. galgo, G. galgen, Icel. g, Sw. & Dan. galge, Goth. galga a cross. Etymologically and historically considered, gallows is a noun in the plural number, but it is used as a singular, and hence is preceded by a; as, a gallows.]"
